        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10778",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I prefer not to put too much effort on the Zend_Http_Client as it is going to be replaced by the incubator Zend_Http_Client which is a complete rewrite. \n\nDo you think this issue concers the new Http_Client as well? This one has easier access to GET parameters and  you could either set them individually using $client->setParameterGet('foo', 'baz'), or directly access the query string by doing this:\n{noformat}\n$client->getUri()->setQuery('foo=baz');\n{noformat}\n\nI'm not sure if any further changes are needed. Let me know what you think.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-06T02:40:27.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-06T02:40:27.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10784",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Oh, I didn't know there was a newer version of Zend_Http_Client coming.  Naturally, any updates to the old one would be a waste of time.\n\nHowever, the changes to Zend_Uri_Http (which are the bulk of my suggestion) would still apply.  I would prefer having the choice of using an array or string, and I'm sure others would as well.\n\nThe changes to Zend_Http_Client also use the native PHP function http_build_query(), which renders Zend_Http_Client::_getParametersRecursive() redundant.\n\nI've only taken a couple of minutes to look at the updated Client, but I'm a bit confused why setting GET parameters is handled in two different places--why there is even that option.  It seems to me that GET should be in one place.  The most obvious choice is in the URI, since Zend_Uri_Http is or will be used in places other than Zend_Http.  In that case, you could simply have setParameterGet() should call $this->uri->setQuery().\n\nWhat do you think?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-06T10:00:39.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-06T10:00:39.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10785",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Incidentally, a single hyphen on either side is probably a poor choice of syntax for \"strikethrough\"...",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-06T10:02:14.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-06T10:02:14.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10793",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I see your point now, and of course using $this->uri->setQuery() will be better, as it uses the native http_build_query().\n\nHowever, I would still like to store the GET parameters in an internal array of the client, and only when the request is sent \"attach\" them to the URI object - and this is important because I want people to be able to set parameters before they set the URI for example, or even set several parameters, then set a URI with it's own parameters, and when the request is sent, not to lose any of them.\n\nDoes this makes sense to you? If so, I'll fix up my _prepare_headers() method to use $this->uri->setQuery().\n\nShahar.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-08T09:28:41.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-08T09:28:41.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10797",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I think that's a good idea, Shahar.\n\nBy the way, I've reconsidered the setQuery() function a little.  It should probably look more like this:\n\n{code}\n\/\/ Zend_Uri_Http\n\n    public function setQuery($query)\n    {\n        $this->_query = $this->_parseQuery($query);\n    }\n\n    protected function _parseQuery($query)\n    {\n        if (empty($query)) {\n            return \"\";\n        }\n\n        $queryArray = array();\n        if (is_array($query)) {\n            $queryArray = $query;\n        } else if (is_string($query)) {\n            parse_str($query, $queryArray);\n        }\n        if (count($queryArray) < 1) {\n            throw new Zend_Uri_Exception('No query parameters found');\n        }\n        $query = http_build_query($queryArray, '', '&amp;');\n        if (!$this->validateQuery($query)) {\n            throw new Zend_Uri_Exception('Invalid query string');\n        }\n        return $query;\n    }\n{code}",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-08T16:46:43.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-08T16:46:43.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10826",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I commited Zend_Uri and Zend_Uri_Http revision 1064 which includes your suggestions, although I modified your code a bit. \n\nPlease take a look at it and let me know what you think (if you want to).\n\nDo not mark this bug as fixed - I'll later proceed to change Zend_Http_Client as well.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-13T16:13:31.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-13T16:13:31.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10828",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Thanks for making the update.  I like the fact that you return the old query in setQuery now.\n\nAs far as the changes in _parseQuery, I debated whether or not to include the parse_str part or not.  The main purpose there was an additional check for string validity.  Which, of course, does not belong in _parseQuery, but validateQuery.\n\nHowever, the regular expression in that method (validateQuery) doesn't seem to adequately cover query string validity.  Would something involving parse_str (perhaps comparing the array it returns to an array generated from manually parsing) be good to add there?",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-13T16:31:40.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-13T16:31:40.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10829",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Brain lapse.  Ignore the parenthetical aside in the last sentence.  :-)",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=mratzloff",
                        "name": "mratzloff",
                        "displayName": "Matthew Ratzloff",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-13T16:33:46.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-13T16:33:46.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/10878",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I think the recent changes to Zend_Http_Client and Zend_Uri_Http solve all issues described here. \nI don't think using parse_str is right because just for validating the string, it's a bit overkill (building up an array and all). The query string can be validated easily with a regexp, as long as you follow the RFC.\n\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2006-09-23T02:46:36.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2006-09-23T02:46:36.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/27557",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=wil",
                        "name": "wil",
                        "displayName": "Wil Sinclair",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Bookkeeping. Closing old issues and assigning them to the person who ultimately resolved the issue.",
